<% content_for :page_title, "About Rails — Rails Stuffs" %>

<div class="page-hero">
  <h1>What you are looking at</h1>
  <p class="lede">A quick map of how a browser request becomes HTML in Rails.</p>
</div>

<div class="prose">
  <h2>Model–View–Controller</h2>
  <p>
    <strong>Routes</strong> in <code>config/routes.rb</code> decide which controller action runs.
    The <strong>controller</strong> loads or saves data through <strong>models</strong> (Active Record) and picks a <strong>view</strong> template to render.
  </p>

  <h2>This project in particular</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><code>HomeController</code> — static-style pages with no database query.</li>
    <li><code>DemoController#time</code> — passes Ruby values from the server into the template.</li>
    <li><code>ArticlesController</code> — full resource lifecycle: list, show, create, update, destroy.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Convention</h2>
  <p>
    File names and class names follow conventions (for example <code>ArticlesController</code> and <code>app/views/articles/</code>),
    so Rails can wire things up with minimal configuration.
  </p>
</div>
